{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_fiji_ver02/data/sn83030214/00175039338/1908041401/0280.xml":{"full_text":"Nem Dork dribunce.\nTT\u00bb nay\nEE\nI SS LR\ny> avig... Ne Wa, mewosmm NEW \u201cYORK. TUESDAY. APRIL 14 1908.\u2014TWELVE PAGES. Soi in PRICE THREE CENTS.\nsr\n\n\nPLAN NEW CHELSEA\nWHILE RUINS SMOKE\nFLAM ES DEVASTATED 350\nprompt Rclicf Measures by State\nand Cities Reduce Suffering\nto Mimimum.\nFLAMEN DEVASTATED 350\nACRES LOSS. 85.575.000,\nprompt Relief Measures by State\nand Cities Reduce Suffering\nto Mimimum.\nBoston, April 13. From the embers of vester.\nday's conflagration in Chelsea there arose to-dav\no well organized movement for aid and relief of\nthe ten thousand homeless, a counting of the\ncost by insurance companies, whose representa.\ntives placed their losses at \u00a33.500,000, and a de\ntermination by the city authorities to rebuil2\nthe 85) acres swept by the flames, where stood\npefore the fire property valued at nearly \u00a36,000,\non\nNo further deaths were reported to-day, and\nof the injured persons taken {o the various hos\ns. only two are believed to be in a critical\ncondition. The three bodies which were taken\ntn the morgue in Boston last night remained un\njdentified to-day.\nRevised figures obtained to-day indicated that\nthe losses were divided, according to the vari\nous classes of property destroyed, as follows:\nChurches and schools, $525,000; public buildings,\n$475,000: factories, business blocks and con\ntents, $825,000; dwelling houses, $3,750,000; to\ntal. \u00a3575,000. The insurance of \u00a73,500,000 is\ngivided among about eighty companies.\nThere was comparatively little suffering re\nported among the fire victims to-day. So prompt\ngnd efficient was the relief work that practically\npo one was without shelter last night. To-day\nthe relief work was taken up by those who han\ndied the Massachusetts fund for San Francisco\nsufferers. Early in the day Mayor Beck issued\ngn appeal to the country, but after a conference\nwith Acting Governor Eben 8. Draper the ap\npeal was amended so as to include only the\nstate. Announcement was made that \u00a315.0600\nhad been raised by subscription in Boston before\nnoon. In addition, the city of Chelsea appro\npriated $1000, and a resolution appropriating\n$100.000 was introduced in the House of Rep\nresentatives. Many neighboring cities an\nnoynced-the starting of subscription papers, and\nthe city governments of others will hold special\nmeetings to take action on the matter. A mes\nsage received from President Roosevelt early in\nthe day expressed sympathy and volunteered the\ngervices of the army and navy.\nIn the mean time the loczl organizations, such\nzc the Associated Charities and the Salvation\nArmy, were perfecting their work, and they pro\nfecsed entire ability to find temporary quarters\nfor all the homeless.\nThe burned district was closely patrolled to\nday by the state militia. The work of the guard,\nhowever, consisted mostly in Keeping people\nfrom venturing too near the standing walls.\nThere was very little property remaining to be\nguarded, so thoroughly had the area been swept\nby the flames. In fact, the underwriters who\nyiewad the ruins to-day saw no prospect of sal\nvege of any description. One street, Broadway,\n%as cleaved and opened to-the-general -publie,\nand as it Jed straight through the heart of the\nruins 2 steady stream of people moved through\nit all day. A few of the ruins smoked lazily\nduring the day and two more oil tanks caught\nfre znd burned themselves out. Other than\nthese there was little left of the fire, and all the\nvisiting apparatus was sent home.\nTHREE DEAD; FIFTY HURT\nNeighboring Cities did Acting\nGovernor Draper Sends $15,000.\nBoston. April 13.\u2014An area of 35 acres of black\nened ruins. representing nearly a quarter of the\ntotal area of the city, marks the scene of the great\nfire which swept through the business section of\nChelsea vesterday and last night. Although only\nthree persons are known to have lost their lives in\nthe fire, over half a hundred persons were in\njured end many were taken to the hospitals suffer\ning severely.\nStaring near the corner of Cypress and 3d\nStreets, from a blaze in a pile of rags on a public\ndumping ground, the blaze spread before a north\neast gale straight across the city to the southeast,\nspreading out as it advanced until its nortlily boun\ndary reached the Eastern division of the Boston\nMaine Railroad. Thence it extended to the junc\ntion of the railroad with the tracks of the Boston\nAlbany Railroad, over which it leaped and then\nswept on until checked by a small creek. On the\nother sige it crept along 24 street until Broadway\nwas reacl,ed and then went along Essex and Mid\nflesex streets to the waterfront at Chelsea Creek.\nThe distance from the point where the fire started\n1 \u201che creck is a mile and a half and the greatest\nwidth of the fire tract is about half a mile. Even\n&t the (reck the fire was not wholly stayed, for\nsparks blown across set fire to several houses and\nto the plant of the Standard Oil Company.\nSUPPLIES SENT IN ABUNDANCE,\nThe relief work early to-day took on a substan\ntizl form, and by noon the situation was well in\nband. Tiere mas clothing in abundance, temporary\nsiclter had been provided for the homeless, and so\nbountiful was the supply of focd brought into the\nFlricken city that no one went hungry. The relief\ntommitiee, composed of Chelsea citizens and or\n#anized ot a meeting last night, was active to-day\nIn relieving the distress.\nCharitetle organizations found places for many\nof the suffercrs. schoolhouses and other public\nbuildings in Boston and other places near the\ntiricken city were thrown open to provide tempo\ntery lodgings, and hundreds of military teuts\nbrouglnt from the state cump grounds at South\nFramingham served as uo protection for victims of\nthe fire 2 Governor Draper early in the\nevening had authorized the city of Chelsea to pro\nCite Provisions for emergency use up to any rea\n#00abie amount at the coxpensc of the state, and\n\u20ac2iry and Lakery companies contributed large sup\nPlies of their products, which found their way\nPromptly to the sufferers.\n2\nWhile prompt measures for caring for the honie\nwere being taken, scores of physicians, nurses\n20d volunteer worke s were attending to the in\nThe Chelsea poli.e statio: was tyrned into\n\nYue\n25 mprompry hospital, and many sufferers were\ntL ere an. treated temporarily. Later, they\nBere sent to the Naval Hospital and the Marine\nWOSpital. Leth of whi bk were packed to the Limit\nof their capacity from this source and trom the\ned Or patients froin the two other hospitals\n8 were burned.\nBTATTER\u2122D BABES FOUND.\nDuring the afiern.on and evening over fifty un\nHdentifieq habie: who had been picked up by the\nPolice, remen and citizens, were taken to the police\nations. They ranged in ge from two months to\nYEars, A boy bought in a baby less than six\nMonths old that he had picked up in the gutter,\nan brought 2 pai= \u00abf boy twins, not more\nBye Year oid. She sad that 2 frantic mother\nor Fangonis the babi inte her arms as she stood\na oa Sioa. \u00a5aying: \"Here hold tliese. I've got\nih i others, What became of the mother\nBome 2 een ascertained zt a late hour to-day.\nOf the derelict in. nts were taken away dur\nthe nigia by 1\u20aclavves, but others remained still\nkicigimey to-day. Among the women taken to\ning\nBTATTER\u2122D BABES FOUND.\nYuring the afrern.on and evening over fifty un\n*ntified Yabie: who had been picked up by the\nPolice, remen and citizens, were taken to the police\n\u00aelations, They ranged in age from two months to\nBre years. A boy nought in a baby less than six\n|ONths old that he had picked up in the gutter.\nA woman brought a pai \u00abf boy twing, not more\nthan 5 Year oid. She sad that 2 frantic mother\nbad thre the babic: inte her arms as she stood\nO0 the strect. saying: \u201cHere hold these. I've got\n19 ger the others. What became of the mother\nbed not been ascertained zt a late hour to-day.\nBome of the derutict in: nts were taken away dur\nthe nigia by 1\u20aclavves, but others remained still\nbicigimed to-day. Among the women taken to\nContinued on second page\nFIND WOMAN CHOKED {WARNING T0.CONGRESN\nMAN SLASHED TO DEATH.\\ PRESIDENT VETOES BILL.\nFIND WOMAN CHOKED\nPNW WAY UHURK LD\nMAN SLASHED TO DEATH,\nThird Victim of Tenderloin Tragedy\nBadly Hurt.\nMAN SLASHED TO DEATH,\nThird Victim of Tenderloin Tragedy\nBadly Hurt.\nA triple tragedy occurred at No. 125 West 28th\nstreet, in the centre of the Tenderloin district, ves\nterday afternoon, which for a time baffled the\npolice.\nA woman whom the detectives recognized as\nKate Pelrer, a character well known in the neigh\nborhood, was found strangled in the bedroom of her\napartments, and in the kitchen an Italian, identi\nfied later as Vital Debella Badia. was found with\nhis threat cut and a large bread Knife lying by his\ngide. The third person connected with the tragedy\nis Charles Berger, who is known to have lived\nwith the dead woman for several months, He is\nnow in the New York Hospital, suffering from stab\nwounds.\nAfter several conflicting stories told to the police\nthey are inclined to accept Rerger\u2019s version of the\ntragedy, and that is that when he entered his\napartments vesterday afternoon he found the Pelter\nwoman lying across the bed and saw Badia tryipg\nto open a desk with a pair of shears. He says he\ngrappled with Badia and received three wounds in\nthe chest.\n\nThe police now believe that an attempt was\nmade by Badia to rob the woman of her jewelry,\nand that when Berger escaped, after a struggle\nwith him, the former went:to the kitchen and cut\nhis throat. This belief was strengthened when an\nexamination of Badia's clothes was made and two\nearrings which Berger identified as belonging to\nthe woman were found on his person.\nShortly after 3 o'clock vesterday Berger was seen\nto run excitedly out of the West 2%th street house,\nand rushing up to Patrolman Houston. of the West\n30th street station, it is said, exclaimed that a\nwoman had been murdered and a man had commit\nted suicide at that address.\nHouston went back with the man and found the\nwoman lying across the bed in her apartments, with\na Turkish towel tied tightly around her throat and\nBadia lying on the Kitchen floor unconscious.\nHouston summoned an ambulance from the New\nYork Hospital and Badia was rushed off in the\nhope that he miglit regain his senses sufficiently to\nmake a statement. He died, however, without re\ngaining consciousness.\n\nThe police had some difficulty mn identifying the\ndead man. It was not until they found Lena Arico,\nwho sald she was his niece, that something could\nbe learned about him. The niece informed the\npolice her uncle's name was Badia, that he was a\nclothes presser, born in Italy, and was forty-six\nvears old. She said that he had lived with another\nwoman in the West 28th street house where the\ncrime was committed.\n\nAssistant District Attorney Simonds, Captain\nFarrell, of the West 30th street police station, and\nCoroner Dooley went to the hospital last night to\nexamine Berger, and when they were through they\nintimated that they were inclined to accept his\nstory that he found Badia in his apartments and\nthat the latter evidently went there to commit rob\nbery.\nAlthough Berger was arrested on the charge of\nhomicide and was detained a prisoner in the hos\npital pending his recovery from his wounds, it is\nbelieved that there is no case against him and that\nin all probability he will be discharged when ar\nraigned before a magistrate.\nAccording to the police, the dead woman three\nvears ago married a man named Pelter, who owned\na restaurant. He died suddenly, and the story\nwent around that he was strangled or poisoned.\nMrs. Pelter was arrested at the sine as a sus\npicious person, but the corons r'sYjury could not\nfind a case against her and she was discharged.\nSince then she lived for some time with Badia,\nand while his money lasted they were often seen\ntogether. It was reported that she then left him,\nand recently went to live with Berger,\nEarly this morning Detectives Sullivan and\nSchueing, of the Central Office, are sted William\nWaissman, a printer, at his home, No. 309 Fast\n6th street, as a malerial witness. He is said to\nbe a brother of the murdered woman.\nWILL OF THOMAS B. WANAMAKER.\nTotal Value of the Estate May Reach\n\u00a310.000,000\u2014Brother Executor.\nPhiladelphia April 12--The will of Thomas BE.\nWanamaker. son of John Wanamaker, who died\nabroad several weeks ago, was admitted to probate\nto-day. With the exception of a few bequests to\nhousehold employes the estate is left to his widow,\nMrs. Mary Lowber Welsh Wanamaker; his mother,\nMrs. Mary B. Wanamaker, his two sisters, Mrs.\nMary B. Warburton and Mrs. Elizabeth Mcleod,\nand his brother, Louis Rodman Wanamaker.\nLouis Rodman Wanamaker is executor, and will\nhave full control of the large estate, including \u201cThe\nNorth American\u201d newspaper. The statement filed\nby the executors appraises the value of the per\nsonal property as $100,600 and upward, with no ap\npraisegaent of the real estate. 1t is understood that\nthe total value of the estate may reach $10,000,000,\nThe will states that provision was made for the\ntestator\u2019s sons during his lifetime.\ney\nPhiladelphia, April 13.\u2014Willlam Renwick, popu\nlarly known as \u201cScotty,\u201d the groundkeeper at the\n1'niversity of Pennsylvania, was struck on the\nhead by a 18-pound hammer at Franklin Field to\nday and probably fatally injured.\nIranicl F. Luby, of Peabody, Mass. threw the\nhammer gown the field toward \u201cScotty,\u201d who either\ndid not sce the throw or lost sight of the weight\ntn the sun\nRUSE CLEARS THEATRE ON FIRE.\nWhen Frederick W. Alles, manager of the Blaney\n_Theatre, in Newark, interrupted the third act of\n\u201cHer Mad Marriage\u2019 last night to announce thut\nthere was a fire a few doors away the large audi\nence quietly left the plavhouse. Outside they\nlearned that the blaze was in the theatre, and then\nin the rush of women and children several were\nkneccked down and trampled.\nCrossed electric light wires in the top gallery\nstarted the fire. Manager Alles, fearing a panic,\nmade the false announcement,\nPittsburg, April 13--Cougressman John Dalaell\nwas not defeated for delegate from the 30ta Dis\ntrict to the Republican National Convention, as\nwas indicated in the carlier returns from Satur\nday's primary election.\n{By Telegraph to The Tribune.\nHAMMER THROWER HITS \u201cSCOTTY.\u201d\nandl\nDAL ZELL WILL BE DELEGATE.\nCHOKED\nGLIMPSES OF CHELSEA, MASS, BEFORE THE FIRE.\nTHE sSQUARE.\n1RnEssSYL ARE.\n(The Rotograph Company.)\nWARNING TO.CONGRESN\nPRESIDENT VETOES BILL.\nSays Valuable Natural Resources\nMust Not Be Given Away.\nWashington, April 13.-\u2014-In a special message\nto-day vetoing a dam bill President Roosevelt\nwarns Congress that there are pending bills\nwhich propose to give away without price rights\nin streams capable of developing 1.300.000\nhorsepower, whose production would cost an\nnually 25,000,000 tons of coal; urges in vigorous\nterms the establishment of a policy which woul.\nsafeguard the granting of bridge and dam privi\nleges and require the grantees to pay for them,\nand definitely announces a future policy on his\npart with regard to prompt utilization of con\nstruction privileges by refusing his signature\nto a bill giving an additional three years to the\nRainy River Improvement Company in which wo\nbuild a dam in the Rainy River.\n\n\u201cI do not believe,\u201d says the President, \u201cthat\nnatural resources should be granted and held in\nan undeveloped condition either for speculative\nor other reasons. So far as I am aware, there\nare no assurances that the grantees (in this\ncase) are in any better condition promptly anil\nproperly to utilize this opportunity than they\nwere at the time of the original act (granting\nthe privilege) ten years ago.\u201d\nTHE PRESIDENT'S MESSAGE.\nDiscussing broadly the federal policy, the\nPresident says:\nEvery permit to construct a dam on a nav\nigable stream should specifically recognize the\nright of the government to fix a term for its\nduration and to impose such charge or charges\nas may be deemed necessary to protect the\npresent and future interests of the United States\nin accordance with the act of June 21, 1906.\nThe provision for a charge is of vital im\nportance. The navigability of every inland\nwaterway and of all connected or connectable\ninland waterways as a whole should be im\nproved for the purposes of interstate and for\neign commeree upon a consistent and unified\nplan by whieh each part should be ..ade to\nhelp every other part.\nThe income derivable from this source would\nmaterially aid in the complete improvement of\nour navigable waters, for which there is now\nsuch a erying need. The chief of engineers of\nthe army reports that the bills now pending at\nthis session of Congress permit the construc\ntion of dams in navigable streams capable of\ndeveloping over 1,300,000 horsepower. These\nrivers run every hour in the day and every day\nin the year. To develop this amount of power\nwouid, under average conditions, require about\n25,000,000 tons of medium quality coal every\nYear. This natural wealth is the heritage of\nthe people. 1 see no reason for giving it away,\nthough there im every reason for not imposing\nconditions so burdensome as to prevent the\nutilization of the power. We are now\nat the beginning of a great development in\nwater power. Its use through electrical trans\nmission is entering more and more largely into\nevery element\u2019 of the daily life of the people.\nAlready the evils of monopoly are becoming\nmanifest; already the experiences of the past\nshow the necessity of caution in making un\nrestricted grants of this great power.\n\nThe present policy pursued in making these\ngrants is unwise in giving away the property\nof the people in the flowing waters to individuals\nor organizations practically unknown and grant\ning in perpetuity these valuable privileges in\nadvance of the formation of definite plans as to\ntheir use. In some cases the grantees apparent\nIy have little or no financial or other ability to\nutilize the gift, and have sought it merely be\ncause it could be had for the asking.\nOUTLINES A DEFINITE POLICY.\nin place of the present haphazard policy of\npermanently alienating valuable public property\nwe should substitute a definite policy along the\nfollowing lines:\nFirst\u2014There should be a limited or carefully\nguarded grant in the nature of an option or op\nportunity afforded within reasonable time for\ndevelopment of plans and tor explanations of the\nproject.\n\nSecond\u2014Such a grant or concession should be\naccompanied in the act making the grant by a\nprovision expressly making it the duty of the\ndesignated official to annul the grant if the work\nis not begun or plans are not carried out in ac\ncordance with the authority granted.\nThird\u20141t should also be the duty of some\ndesignated official to sce to it that in approving\nthe plans the maximum development of the\nnavigation and power is assured, or at least that\nin making the plans these may not be so de\nveloped as ultimately to interfere with the bet\nter utilization of the water or complete develop\nment of the power.\n\nFourth\u2014There should be a license fee or\ncharge which. though small or nominal at the\noutset, can in the future be adjusted so as to\nsecure a control in the interest of the public.\nFifth-\u2014Provision should be made for the ter\nmination of the grant or privilege at a definite\ntime, leaving to future generations the power\nor authority to renew or extend the concession\nin accordance with the conditions which may\nprevail at that time\nRe A C\u2014O Ml ee A\ni i a J\nTHE MINISTRY COMPL KTE\nNew Parliamentary  Sceretaries\u2014\nLeader in Upper House.\nLondon, April 13.--H. H. Asquith, the Pre\nmier, completed the reorganization of the min\nistry to-flay as follows:\nCC. F. H. Hobhouse, at present Parliamentary\nSecretary to the Indian Office, becomes Finan\ncial Secretary to the Treasury; T. J. Macnamara,\nnow Parliamentary Secretary to the Local Gov\nernment Board, becomes Parliamentary Secre\ntary to the Admiralty; C. F. G. Masterman,\nLiberal Member of Parliament for West Ham,\nbecomes Parliamentary Secretary to the Local\nGovernment Board, and Thomas McKinnon\nWood, Liberal Member of Parliament for Glas\ngow, becomes Partiamentary Secretary to the\nBoard of Trade,\nThe Marquis of Ripon remains Lord Privy\nSeal, but at his request the Earl of Crewe, Lord\nPresident of the Council, will be the leader of\nthe House of Lords\nCENTRAL K. R. OF N. J. AND TO. OHIO\nni OF N. J. AND SAIS\nCENTRAL KE. R. OF N. J. AND BALTO. OHIO\nROYAL BLUE LINE ROUTE\nwill oti April 15'h inaugurate through Parlor Car\nservice between New York and Richmond, Vo\nleaving 23d St. 9:50 8 mm. ~nd Liberty St. 10 a. wm\ndaily except Sunday. App hy nt 'Tieket Offices, 434\n1800 Ercadway, and 20d Street Stanoa.~\u2014Advt.\n(The Rotograph Cempany.)\nWHOLE STATE AROUSED\nWHOLE ST ATE AROUSED FORTUNE FORST. LUKE'S\nHOPE FOR RACING BILLS.| GETS NEARLY $3,000.00\nHOPE FOR RACING BILLS.\nRumor That Votes Will Change\u2014\nGovernor Urged to Speak.\n[By Telegraph to The Tribune.)\n[By Telegraph to The Tribune.)\nAlbany, April 13.\u2014All parts of this state are\naroused over the defeat of the Governor's anti\nracetrack legislation through eight Republican\nvotes and the open manifestations of political\nhatred toward the Governor of a few of the\nleaders of his own party. So freciy is this in\ndignation expressed, and so ready have the\npeople shown themselves to follow the Governor\nin his fight, that already it is said here that\nsome of the Republicans who voted against the\nbills will vote for them if they get another\nchance, while far sighted politicians are be\nginning to predict party disaster this autumn\nif a certain faction of the Republican party\npersists in its efforts to discredit the Governor.\nFrom all sides letters and telegrams are pour\ning into the executive chamber bearing requests\nfor the Governor to make addresses in support\nof his anti-gambling campaign. If he accepted\nhalf of them he could address two meetings a\nday from now until July. Friends who accom\npanied Governor Hughes on his trip to Water\ntown and Buffalo say the bitter resentment ex\npressed privately and publicly over the defeat of\nthe anti-gambling bills was remarkable. At\nBuffalo after the Governor had made his ad\ndress a throng of thousands surged around him\nto grasp his hand and assure him of their sup\nport in his effort to abolish gambling. At Utica\nyesterday there was a similar demonstration.\nIn the districts of the Republican Senators\nwho voted agaipst this legislation the feeling\nseems most intense. Round robins are being\ncirculated in Elmira and the outlying districts\nof Chemung County denouncing Senator Owen\nCassidy and threatening to elect this autumn\nsomebody who will represent the sentiment of\nhis district accurately. These are being signed\nby Republicans of every grade. Chemung\nCounty has not yet instructed for Cassidy's re\nnomination. \"The Ticga County organization,\nled by William Smythe, has instructed its dele\ngates for Cassidy, but one of the leading mem\nbers of the Smythe organization to-day con\nfided to friends that the feeling in that county\nwas so bitter that the delegates might easily\nbolt their instructions. The Winters faction in\nTioga is denouncing Cassidy as a traitor and a\nrenegade.\nSenator Wemple, of Schenectady, under the\ninfluence of John Sanford, of the State Racing\nCommission, voted against the bills. His new\ndistrict comprises Schenectady, Montgomery,\nwith the Sanford power dominant, and Scho\nharie, a Democratic county. The city of\nSchenectady is supposed to be accustomed to\nthe accompaniments of a \u201cwide open\u201d adminis\ntration, yet last night there was a large meet\ning there which excoriated Wemple.\nSenator Grattan, of Albany, whose mother and\nbrother urged him to stand out against the whip\nof William Barnes, jr., and vote for the bills\ninstead of against them, is getting letters each\nday which make his face_carry a sober look.\nA union service of Protestant churches in\nCohoes, his home town, last night adopted\nresolutions calling on him to change his vote\nwhen the bills come up again.\nGovernor Hughes expects to make addresses\nin the next few weeks\u2014as many as he can with\nout detriment to the regular course of his ex\necutive routine. It is entirely probable that one\nof the first, and from a spectacular point of view\none of the most important, will be delivered\nhere in Albany. To-day representatives of the\nCivic I.eague, which for two years has been\nfighting the Barnes local adminstration in an\neffort to clean out the gambling houses and the\nTenderloin district, called on the Governor with\na request that he address a mass meeting. He\nhas not given a final answer yet, but his friends\nexpect him to speak and make emphatic re\njoinder to William Barnes, jr., who every few\ndays takes occasion publicly to denounce the\nGovernor's policies and performances and to\nridicule his views.\n\nThe Governor at Watertown made a thinly\nveiled allusion to Barnes and his course in\nswinging Grattan from his publicly announced\nintention to vote for the anti-gambling bills.\n\u201c1 believe in party organization,\u201d said the\nGovernor, \u201cbut I do not believe In the dictation\nof petty satraps. What a sorry thing it is when\na man can bully a Senator of the state of New\nYork into voting against his conscience. This\nis not the leader who makes the party great.\u201d\nSpeaker Wadsworth to-day declared his belief\nthat the Republican candidate for Senator in\nthe Niagara-oOrleans district, where the Governor\nhas called\u2019 a special election, would he pledged\nto vote for the anti-gambling bills. If not\npledged formally, the Speaker said, he believed\nthe question would be made such a vital issue\nthat the candidate would have to declare him\nself for the bills,\n\u201cIt's a bad mess up there,\u201d said the Speaker,\nreferring to the factional fight Letween the Mer\nritt-Wadsworth and Porter-Stevens forces.\n\u201cNeither facticn, so far as I know, vet has a\ncandidate, and we may not have any fight over\nthis. But even at that the result will be very\nclose.\u201d The Speaker said that if the Governor\nstumped that district it would be a considerable\nhelp to the Republican candidate\nAsked about the truth of a report that the del\negates from that Congress district to the Chi\ncago convention would not vote for Governor\nHughes, the Speaker said: \u201cI do not like to\nanticipate any action, but 1 expect to he a dele\ngate to Chicago from that district, and if IT am\n1 shall vote for the Governor.\u201d\nThe Speaker made no hesitation about saying\nthat he thought the Assembly had finished its\nconsideration of the Governor's direct nomina\nContinued on second pags.\nContinued on second pags.\nTHE COURTHOUSE.\n\u00a31 sunt Ss\nwd BLL RB\noc,\nbh\ni\nFORTUNE FORST. LUKE'S\nGETS NEARLY $3,000.00\nWW. W. Smith, Architect, Bequeaths\nBulk of Estate to Hospital.\nBy the will of William W neeler smith, an ar\nchitect, of No. 3 Wall street. which was filed on\nFriday, the endowment fund of St. Luke's Hos\npital is increased vearly by the revenue on\nnearly $3.0060.000 worth of property in this city,\nall of which will become the property of the hos\npital on the death of Mrs. Smith. The large\nzift seemed to have been overlooked at first, ow\ning to the modest way in which the will was\nfiled.\nThe properties mentioned in the will are the\nbuildings at Nos. 3, 5 and 7 Wall street and No.\n71 Wall street, hoth large office buildings in the\nheart of the financial district. The former build\ning extends back to No. 84 Broadway and is\nvalued at $3.500000, with a mortgage of \u00a31.400,\n000. The other building is valued at $550,000,\nwith a mortgage of $300,060. In addition to\nthis Mr. Smith left three hundred shares of West\nShore Railroad stock and his home at No. 17\nWest TTth street, which is subject td a mort\ngage of $22,000.\nRBv the terms of the will $5,000 was left to a\ncoustn, Walter 8. Howell, of Goshen, N. Y.;\n{5.000 to another cousin, John Miller Burt, of\nWarwick. N. Y.. and other bequests of $8,000 to\nfamily servants. The house at No. 17 East 77th\nstreet was left. to Mrs. Smith, with all of the\ncontents. to Jo with as she wished, and a yearly\nallowance from the No. 3, 5 and 7 Wall street\nproperty. Ry the provisions of the will the\nrevenue of the No. 71 Wall street property was\nto go for the benefit of the Association for the\nRelief of Respectable, Aged and Indigent Fe\nmales, at Amsterdam avenue and 104th street,\nbut this was revoked in a codical to the will, in\nwhich this property was to be added to the bLe\nquest to St. Luke's Hospital.\nIn making the bequest to St. Luke's Hospital\nMr. Smith stipulates that the money be applied\n\u201cto the care and reiief of needy convalescent\npatients recovering from acute diseases and sur\ngical operations and from these and other\ncauses requiring care and treatment not obtain\nable in their homes, and without regard to ire\nligious belief or sex.\u201d Mr. Smith's attorney,\nJudson B. Wilds, and the United States Trust\nCompany are appointed trustees of the estate,\nand they are given full right to administer it\nto the best of their judgment.\nAt the death of Mrs. Smith the property will\nall go to St. Luke's Hospital Corporation, or if\nit has been sold the money will revert to the\nhospital. In the will Mr. Smith signified a desire\nthat if his wishes were followed out the plot\ne. tending from Nos. 3, 5, T Wall street back\nto No. S41 Broadway should only be used for\none building, and that it should never be sold\nfor less than $3,000,000, and he was of the\nopinion that the building should be sold to some\nhigh class established corporation, bank or trust\ncompany or some interest facilating such a\nresult as he desired. In regard to his stocks\nhe expressed a wish that they should never be\nsold unless to buy equally high class stocks\nvielding an income of $10,006.\nMr. Wilds was not \u2018willing last night to place\na valuation on the property that will some day\nbecomes St Luke's Hospital, or say how much it\nwould receive vearly, but according to the esti\nmates the whole estate minus mortages is valued\nat between S20500,000 and $3,000 000. Mr. Wilds\ngave no reason for his client's having by the\ncodicil cut off the bequest to the Home for\nRespectable Aged and Indigent Femafes, nor\ndid Mrs. Smith.\nMr. Smith was born in this city in 1838, and\nentered the office of James Renwick, a well\nknown architect, in 1857, where he remained\nuntil 1861, when he went abroad to study at the\nUniversity of London. After remaining there\nfor eighteen months, he travelled on the Con\ntinent, and, returning to New York, entered\nbusiness fgr himself. He soon became well\nknown in the profession. His most notable\nworks were the Collegiate Dutch Church, at\nFifth avenue and 48th street, which was dedi\ncated in June, 1870; the Ccllege of Physicians\nand Surgeons, the Sleane Maternity Hospital,\nthe Syms Clinic and the Manhattan Building, in\nWall street.\nMr. Smith married Catherine H. Brown, and,\nsave her, leaves no immediate family. He was\na member of the Union League and Grolier\nclubs, the Bibliophile Scciety of Boston the\nMuseum of Natura! History and the Metropoli-\ntan Museun:.\nRETURN OF PROSPERITY PREDICTED.\nSeymour Bell, British Commercial Agent\nHere, Expresses Honeful Views\nLondon, April 13.\u2014Seymour Bell. British commer\ncial agent in the United States. in a report on\nAmerican trade for 197, which has just been issued\nby the Board of Trade, takes a hopeful view of the\nfuture. He says that the farmers, who form the\nhackbone of American prosperity, have not been\naffected by the financial erisis, and that the coun\ntry is producing crops valued at nearly $7,500.000.000.\nThe country, Mr. Bell thinks, is not likely long to\nsuffer from industrial stagnation: He predicts a\nquiet business in 1%8 and thinks the return to the\nnormal condition of affairs will depend largely on\nthe crops.\nBarcelona, April 13.\u2014J\u00e9an Rull and three of his\naccomplices who have been on triar here for com\nplicity mm ihe recent series of bomb explosions and\nanarchist outrages were fonnd guilty to-day. Tes\ntimony showed that Rull and his associates were\nthe authors of the attempts to assassinate King\nAlfonso at Madrid and Paris and of various out\nrages in differant parts of Spain\nRull was sentenced to death and the others to\nHnprigonment.\nDEWEY'S CLARETS AND OLD BURGUNDY.\nTuken with the Meal enriches the blood\nH T. Dewey Sons Ce, 133 Fultun St, New York\nwAdVE\na\nANARCHISTS CONVICTED IN SPAIN\n83.000 000,\n\u201cLONG PATS\" COUP\nSTARTLES REGULARS\nMURPHY-CONNERS FORCE\nTIED UP BY COURT.\nEn joined from Qusting Kings Men\nHill Seek to Dhscredit Mec\n\u201cLONG PATN\u2122 COUP\nSTARTLES REGULARS\nMURPHY-CONNERS FORCE\nTIED UP BY COURT.\nTIED UP BY COURT.\nEnjoined from Ousting Kings Men\nWill Seek to Discredit Me\nan\nCarren in Convention.\nvisage and IMroapeCt ye A Ea. Be a\nF. Murphy and William J. Conners another\nvoluable lesson in politics vesterday, at ths\nmeeting of the Democratic State Committee, at\nthe Hotel Vietoria, when he tied them up hard\nand fast with a Supreme Court order which\nwill prevent them, temporarily at least, from\nthrowing out forty-eight :iate convention dele\ngates from sixteen districts in Kings, who Mr\nMcCarren savs were honestly elected\nhe of the sad\nProfessor Patrick H. McCarren,\nMessrs. Murphy and Conners had things\npretty well fixed to name a credentials com-=\nmittee of \u201ctrusties.\u201d decide the contest: in Kings\nagainst McCarren, make the Senator look cheap,\nand carry the war against him into the Septem\nber primaries, when they hope to kill him off.\nSenator McCarren is willing to be the under\ntaker at a respectable Democratic political fun=\neral. but never the corpse. His obstinacy in this\nrespect is becoming a fixed habit. much to tha\nchagrin of Messrs. Murphy and Conners.\nJustice Crane, of Brooklyn, issued a blanket\ninjunction yesterday morning against the Demo=\ncratic State Committee and the committees on\ncredentials of the state convention, ordering\nthem to show cause why the delegates from\nKings County, regularly elected at the primaries,\nshoyld not be placed on the temporary roll\ncall of the convention and have their seats.\nThe order was granted on the application of\nIsaac M. Kapper, representing the Democratic\nGeneral Committee of Kings County. It is\nreturnable to-morrow morning when Mr. Me\nCarren and his friends will be re dy for the legal\nbattle.\nIt looks as if McCarren\u2019's men would keep their\nseats. Charles F. Murphy said last night that\nthe order of the Supreme Court would be re\nspected and that the McCarren men would go\non the temporary roll of the convention\nAs soon as the injunction was served on Chair=\nman Conners a conference of the MurphyCon\nners men was summoned. Daniel F. Ceohalan,\nchairman of the law committee of Tammany\nHall, hurried downtown to see some of the fus\ntices about a vacation of the order. He proba=\nbiy was told that ne justice would relish the job\nof vacating Justice Crane's order before the hour\nset for its return to-morrow.\nMURPHY-CONNERS COUNTER MOVE\nSenator MecCarren's injunction disconcerted\nthe Murphy-Conners men. Daniel F. Cohalan,\nchairman of the Tammany law committee, was\nin conference last night with various members\nof the committee, and as a result of their con\nference Chairman Conners late last night sent\nout a call for a meeting of the state committee\nat the Victoria at 10 o'clock this forenoon.\nIt seems to be the intention of the Murphy\nConners men to put McCarren in the light of 2\ndisturber and make him \u201cirregular,\u201d so that any\naction taken by the state committee or the stale\nconvention can be justified. If there is any way\nto do it without getting tangled up in the courts\nthe Murphy-Conners men will not only throw\nthe most of McCarren's delegates out of the\nconvention to-morrow, but afterward, if they\ncan do it. they will put him off the state com\nmittee and fill the places of the McCarren stats\ncommitteemen with his enemies. Borougn\nPresident Coler and his secretary, Mr. Heffer\nnan, were in conference at a late hour last night\nat the Waldorf-Astoria with Chairman Conners.\n\u201cI told Mr. Coler that MecCarren's men wera\nlikely to stay on the roll,\u201d said Mr. Conners.\nSenator McCarren said that as soon as the\ntemporary organization of the convention was\neffected to-day he would serve the injunction en\nthe temporary officers. The anti-McCarrenites\nsaid last night that they did not wish to throw\nout all of the Senator's delegates. They said\nthat the district leaders, Regan, of the 35th;\nHasenflug, of the 19th, and Butler, of the 1lta,\nwould be allowed to retain their secats.in con\nvention as well as the seven leaders who joined\nthe insurrection against McCarren the week be\nfore the primaries. They are Melody, Gray.\nLynch, Byrnes, Doyle, Farrell and Sinnott.\nA TWO DAYS CONVENTION.\nAll the indications peint to a two days\u2019 con=\nvention. The first session will be called to or\nder at 12 o'clock to-day, when a temporary or\nganization will be effected. Thomas F. Car\nmody, of Penn Yan, will be the temporary and\npermanent chairman. He will appoint the vari\nous committees, the most important being the\ncommittee on credentials.\nThe secretaries will be John A. Mason,\nThomas F. Smith. John F. Nahar, John P. Zen\nter and John C. McDonald.\nThere are so many contests that it will be im=\npracticable to get through with them to-day.\nSecretary Mason received notices of contests as\nfollows:\nAlbany County\u2014lst, 2d and 3d districts, Jacob\nL. Ten Eyck contestant\nChautauqua County\u20141st District, Frank H.\nMott contestant.\nHerkimer County\u2014Addison G. Gehman con=\ntestant.\nErie County\u20149th District, Edward E. Coates.\nworth contestant.\nJefferson County\u20141st District, Charles H.\nJerome contestant; 2d, Andrew C. Cornwall\nQueens County \u2014Joseph Bermel contestant.\nLittle was talked about at the meoting of the\nstate committee at the Hotel Victoria vesterday\nbut the McCarren injunction. It was entirely\nunexpected. McCarren did not believe William\nJ. Conners, state chairman, who kept assuring\nthe McCarren men that they would get a square\ndeal, ete. Mec(arren saw the Bermel men\nthrown out at Buffalo two years ago by Mur\nphy. Conners. Cockran and Grady. He was con\nscious of the fact that contests had been brought\nagainst him in sixteen districts in Kings, and\nhe believes that Murphy and Conners are flirt.\ning with Borough President Coler, who hopes to\nrun for Governor next fall. That is why he got\nthe court order.\nThe order was served on a majority of the\nstate committee. The affidavit sets forth that\nthe contestants had had two weeks in which\nto appeal to the courts and set in motion a pro\nceeding to prove their rights te the seats held\n1 the McCarren men, and that they had made\nno move,\nSENATOR MUCARREN'S VIEW.\nSENATOR MUARRENS VIEW.\nWhen Senator McCarren was seen last night\nhe said: \u201cOur men were honestly elected. and\nwe purpose to hold on if we can. We would\nnot have taken this action if we had not had\nzovd reason for so doing The state committea\nhas obeyed the court order and our men go on\ntha temporary roll. After the temporary or\n\u2018&anization is effected to-morrew the chairman","height":"35400","width":"25952"}}
